defaultthe NCRS rules 
defaultsometimes 
defaulttake an element of this away from them.
default&#xa0;
defaultLocally, we have tended to take a risk-averse approach to the re
defaultcording of crime.  This has arguably been a contributory factor in our higher levels of crime when compared to our peers.  This makes comparison difficult, but also raises the question over
default whether it is possible or even necessary to have national comparat
defaultive statistics, especially as the focus of Police and Crime Commissioners is 
defaultpredominantly 
defaulton local provision.  It also raises the question over whether a national standard for crime recording
default should continue to be 
defaultviewed as achievable or even necessary.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe other thing we have to remember with recorded crime statistics is that whilst the ‘traditional’ crimes (burglary, vehicle crime, and so on) are falling, fraud is replacing such crimes as the offence of choice for an increasing number of 
defaultoffenders
default.  The
default clear message needs to be that whilst
default other reported crime decreases,
default fraud in the 
defaultUK
default is growing.  We also know that a large volume of fraud remains unreported, due to a number of factors such as victimisation of vulnerable and hard 
defaultto reach groups, and w
defaulte do not know the full scale of the threat and its impact on 
defaultour 
defaultlocal communities.  By focusing on ‘traditional’ crime recording, we are al
defaultso in fear of putting
default our resources 
defaultnot
default in the places where they are most needed and will reap 
defaultthe greatest benefit 
