defaultQuestion 2: Whatdefault are the factors which can influence police mis-recording of crime?default&#xa0;
defaultFollowing on from Question 1, they key issue 
defaultis the time-frame for criming.
default&#xa0;
defaultI believe 
defaultwe need to 
defaultquestion whether the police are sometimes too quick to crime an incident before taking in
defaultto account the victims wishes and feelings.  The NCRS rules have to some extent taken away the common-sense element of policing.  There is no doubt in my mind that recording rules are a necessity, but we need to look 
defaultpotentially 
defaultat a ‘cooling off’ period 
defaultf
defaultor certain crime types and 
defaultthe ability for discretion by police officers to take what they consider to be an appropriate response (which might not include criming), 
defaultwhilst 
defaultultimately record what is right after taking 
defaultsuch 
defaulttime and accounting for the victim
defaults needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe removal of the target culture has 
defaultundoubtedly 
defaulthelped in reducing the possibility 
defaultof 
default‘gaming’ by 
defaultofficers categorising crime
defaults
default incorrectly, e.g. criming a dwelling burglary as a theft from dwelling when they may have reached their ‘quota’ of dw
defaultelling burglaries for the month.  This type of activity must be discouraged and the removal of a target culture helps in this respect.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, the over reliance on quantitative data combined with simplistic and inappropriate centrally set targets in 
defaultthe past has, in my opinion, 
defaultcorrupted policing and led to perverse outcomes, devoid of common sense that has undermined public confidencedefault.
