defaultQuestion 3: Are the right checks in place to ensure that the systems for recording crime functiondefaultsdefault effectively and accurately?default&#xa0;
defaultThe Police and Crime Commissioners are there to hold their Chief Constable to account on behalf of the public.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe question we need to ask is whether public perception of crime recording reflects the reality.  It is important
default that systems are in place locally and that they are effective for local circumstances.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn Humberside, as part of my Police and Crime Plan, I will be rolling out mobile technology to ensure officers are visible in our local neighbourhoods
default and
default in the place
defaults where they are most required.  We need to
default recognise the risks in rolling-
defaultout such technology
default, 
defaultensuring the correct impact on crime recording, consistency and the use of common-sense by officers to individual situations.
default&#xa0;
defaultI am aware of the work by Her Maj
defaultesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary (HMIC) around data integrity.  This relies on a limited sample and doesn’t fully take into account the work undertaken by local Crime Registrars
default in their audits, findings and learning points.  This local element to me is
default important to 
defaultensure that 
defaultour
default systems locally are as effective and accurate as they can be.  We need to create an atmosphere where we do things right for the victim in the first instance and correct any issues 
defaultquickly 
defaultif things do not go as expected.
default&#xa0;
defaultI wi
defaultll give an example where it could be questioned whether crimes are being recorded accurately.  Locally we have a high incidence of criminal damage (a crime) and a low incidence of anti-social behaviour (an incident).  It could be argued that we have taken 
defaulta risk-averse approach to recording, hence the high-level of criminal damage.  Less risk-averse approaches could produce a more 
default‘
defaultbalanced
default’
default level of crimes and incidents.  Our approach indicates that we could be over-recording criminal damage, although our 
defaultdata integrity audits show that NCRS compliance is excellent, i.e. we’re 
defaultnot
default over-recording.  
defaultBut this raises two questions: (i) whether othe
defaultrs are following a similar line
default and (ii) 
defaultthe 
defaultcomparability of figures between forces.
