defaultQuestion 5: To what extent can policy-makers have confidence in the statistics which result from the recording of crime by police forces?default&#xa0;
defaultIt is important for 
defaultPolice and Crime Commissioners to have confidence in the
defaultir
default statistics locally in order to hold to account the Chief Constable on behalf of the public.  This is impo
defaultrtant for me at a local level.
default&#xa0;
defaultI 
defaultam 
defaultuncertain as to the level of confidence within other po
defaultlice forces and the ability for national policy-makers to have confidence in this data.  However, the duties of the Police and Crime Commissioner are clear
default,
default and if they are undertaken adequately then confidence in the data should be high.
default&#xa0;
defaultQuestion 6: Shoudefaultld recorded crime statistics be classified as National Statistics?default&#xa0;
defaultIt is important that the statistics are accurate at a local level as part of my statutory duties.  
defaultThe focus on local solutions through local statistics must be the way forward in the firs
defaultt instance.
default&#xa0;
defaultI believe that the National Statistics can be unrepresentative of the local picture.  In addition, the Office of National Statistics (ONS) now tend to produce quarterly figures which are devoid of context and tend to merely restate th
defaultose
default figures presented to them in the first 
defaultinstance
default.  This is due in part to the risk-averse nature of crime statistics publications.  However, the ONS has produced guidance on the publication of local data which is useful to follow.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe also need to bear in 
defaultmind that we should all move away from the current culture of the recorded crime data being seen as the ‘result’ which is then often used as the stick.  We need to move to a place where the figures are used as ‘guidance’, for what they tell us as part of a
defaultn overall holistic assessment of performance.  This includes a mixture of local qualitat
defaultive as well as quantitative data
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultFinally, we need to publish statistics with con
defaulttext and in a manner which incentivises 
defaultpeople 
defaultto 
defaultreporting and/or forces 
defaultto 
defaultrecord.  
defaultThe clearest examples are the increasing rates of sexual crime and 
defaultdomestic violence that are evident throughout many parts of the country at present.  Such rises are depicted by the media and others as failure, whereas what they actually demonstrate is su
defaultccess through partnership working and the increase in the confidence of victims to report the crime by the variety of means we make available to them.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe more serious crimes tend to be grossly underreported and we must make all efforts to encourage repor
defaultting of such crimes.
